         <abstract>
            <p>One of the recent problem-solving financial innovations is a puttable common stock. At a predetermined time, say at the end of two years, the issuer guarantees to support a stated floor value of the puttable stockholder's position. For financial reporting purposes, issuing puttable stock is an equity financing. From the investor's viewpoint, however, puttable stock is comparable to a convertible bond. Tax considerations do not adequately explain the invention of this hybrid security, but informational asymmetry and other market imperfections provide good reasons for this innovation and its potential future use. Based on these conclusions it is predicted that puttable stock has the potential to solve some of the problems arising from informational asymmetry in initial public offerings as well as unique agency problems arising from special classes of common stock (such as the "E class" issued by General Motors).</p>
         </abstract>
